---
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

// --- METADATA ---
export const meta = {
  title: "Microsoft Corporation (MSFT) Intrinsic Value - Gemini's DCF Analysis",
  description: "An independent discounted cash flow (DCF) intrinsic value analysis of Microsoft Corporation (MSFT) compiled entirely by Gemini 2.5 Pro.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-18",
};

// --- DATA & ASSUMPTIONS (FY2025 Actuals) ---
// Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro
// FCF Growth (Y1-Y5): 12%. Massive AI infrastructure investments compress near-term FCF margins, but Azure and Copilot revenue growth provides a very strong floor.
// Discount Rate (WACC): 8.8%. Microsoft has a AAA-rated fortress balance sheet. The 4.18% risk-free rate plus a standard equity risk premium for a low-beta software monopoly yields an 8.8% hurdle.
// Terminal Growth: 3.5%. The sticky nature of Windows, Office 365, and Azure guarantees MSFT grows faster than global GDP in perpetuity.

const baseFCF = 71611; // in Millions (Most recent FY)
const sharesOut = 7425; // in Millions
const currentPrice = 395.50; // Current market price
const netCash = 33967; // Cash & ST investments - Total Debt (in Millions)

const fcfGrowthRate = 0.12;
const discountRate = 0.088;
const terminalGrowthRate = 0.035;

// --- YEAR 1 TO 5 PROJECTIONS ---
const projections = [];
let prevFCF = baseFCF;

for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  const projectedFCF = prevFCF * (1 + fcfGrowthRate);
  const discountFactor = Math.pow(1 + discountRate, i);
  const pvOfFCF = projectedFCF / discountFactor;

  projections.push({
    year: `Year ${i}`,
    fcf: projectedFCF,
    pv: pvOfFCF
  });

  prevFCF = projectedFCF;
}

const sumPvFcf = projections.reduce((sum, p) => sum + p.pv, 0);

// --- TERMINAL VALUE ---
const year5FCF = projections[4].fcf;
const terminalValue = (year5FCF * (1 + terminalGrowthRate)) / (discountRate - terminalGrowthRate);
const pvTerminalValue = terminalValue / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, 5);

// --- ENTERPRISE & EQUITY VALUE ---
const enterpriseValue = sumPvFcf + pvTerminalValue;
const equityValue = enterpriseValue + netCash;
const intrinsicValuePerShare = equityValue / sharesOut;

// --- VERDICT MATH ---
const upside = ((intrinsicValuePerShare - currentPrice) / currentPrice) * 100;
const isUndervalued = intrinsicValuePerShare > currentPrice;
const verdictText = isUndervalued ? "UNDERVALUED" : "OVERVALUED";
const verdictColor = isUndervalued ? "#10b981" : "#ef4444"; // Green vs Red

// --- SENSITIVITY MATRIX ---
const drRange = [0.068, 0.078, 0.088, 0.098, 0.108]; // WACC
const tgrRange = [0.025, 0.030, 0.035, 0.040, 0.045]; // Terminal Growth

const sensitivityMatrix = drRange.map((dr) => {
  return tgrRange.map((tgr) => {
    let loopSumPv = 0;
    let loopPrevFCF = baseFCF;
    for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
      loopPrevFCF = loopPrevFCF * (1 + fcfGrowthRate);
      loopSumPv += loopPrevFCF / Math.pow(1 + dr, i);
    }
    const loopY5 = loopPrevFCF;
    const loopTV = (loopY5 * (1 + tgr)) / (dr - tgr);
    const loopPvTV = loopTV / Math.pow(1 + dr, 5);
    const loopEqVal = loopSumPv + loopPvTV + netCash;
    return loopEqVal / sharesOut;
  });
});

// Formatting Helpers
const formatCurrency = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(val);
const formatMillions = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(val);

// --- JSON-LD SCHEMA ---
const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Gemini 2.5 Pro"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
    "logo": {
      "@type": "ImageObject",
      "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/logo.png"
    }
  },
  "datePublished": meta.published,
  "mainEntityOfPage": {
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "@id": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/microsoft-intrinsic-value"
  }
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/microsoft-intrinsic-value" schema={schema}>

  <article class="study-container">

    <header class="gemini-header">
      <div class="badge">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</div>
      <h1>Microsoft Corporation (MSFT) Intrinsic Value</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">An independent discounted cash flow (DCF) intrinsic value analysis generated purely by AI logic.</p>
    </header>

    <!-- VERDICT CARD -->
    <section class="verdict-card" style={`border-top: 4px solid ${verdictColor}`}>
      <div class="verdict-header">
        <h2>Gemini's Valuation Verdict</h2>
        <div class="verdict-tag" style={`background-color: ${verdictColor}20; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}`}>
          {verdictText}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict-stats">
        <div class="stat-box">
          <span class="stat-label">Intrinsic Value</span>
          <span class="iv-value">{formatCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-box">
          <span class="stat-label">Current Price</span>
          <span class="price-value">{formatCurrency(currentPrice)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-box">
          <span class="stat-label">Premium / Discount</span>
          <span class="upside-value" style={`color: ${verdictColor}`}>
            {upside > 0 ? '+' : ''}{upside.toFixed(2)}%
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="content-body">
      <h2>Methodology & Assumptions</h2>
      <p>
        As an AI model analyzing Microsoft's cash generation capabilities, I have selected a standard
        two-stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) model. This approach attempts to estimate the present value
        of all future free cash flows Microsoft will generate, adjusting for the time value of money and the
        inherent risk of holding the equity.
      </p>

      <div class="assumptions-grid">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="card-top">
            <h3>FCF Growth (Y1-Y5)</h3>
            <span class="assumption-val">{(fcfGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            Microsoft's aggressive capital expenditures in AI data centers are currently suppressing Free Cash Flow
            growth slightly below their explosive revenue growth. However, a 12% growth rate is highly conservative
            given the near-monopoly pricing power of Office 365 Copilot and Azure's immense scalability over the next five years.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="card-top">
            <h3>Discount Rate (WACC)</h3>
            <span class="assumption-val">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            Using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM). With the US 10-Year Treasury yield at 4.18%, a beta of 1.2,
            and an estimated equity risk premium of 4.5%, Microsoft's cost of equity lands near 9.5%. Factoring in
            their AAA-equivalent debt profile slightly lowers their Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) to 8.8%.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="card-top">
            <h3>Terminal Growth</h3>
            <span class="assumption-val">{(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            A 3.5% terminal growth rate assumes Microsoft outpaces global GDP inflation perpetually. Given the ultimate
            stickiness of enterprise software ecosystems, escaping Microsoft's gravity is virtually impossible for
            modern corporations, justifying a premium terminal rate.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Step 1: Free Cash Flow Projections</h2>
      <p>Starting with the most recent trailing twelve months (TTM) Free Cash Flow of <strong>${formatMillions(baseFCF)} million</strong>, we project out five years at {(fcfGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}% growth, discounting back to present value using our {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}% discount rate.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Projected FCF (M)</th>
              <th>Present Value (M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {projections.map(p => (
              <tr>
                <td>{p.year}</td>
                <td class="num">${formatMillions(p.fcf)}</td>
                <td class="num">${formatMillions(p.pv)}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td>Sum of PV (Y1-5)</td>
              <td></td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(sumPvFcf)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Step 2: Terminal Value Calculation</h2>
      <p>Next, we calculate the Terminal Value at the end of Year 5 using the Gordon Growth Model, and discount it back to today.</p>

      <div class="math-box">
        <div class="math-row">
          <span>Year 5 FCF</span>
          <span class="num">${formatMillions(year5FCF)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="math-row">
          <span>Terminal Growth Rate</span>
          <span class="num">{(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</span>
        </div>
        <div class="math-row">
          <span>Terminal Value (End of Y5)</span>
          <span class="num">${formatMillions(terminalValue)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="math-row highlight">
          <span>Present Value of Terminal Value</span>
          <span class="num">${formatMillions(pvTerminalValue)}</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Step 3: Final Valuation</h2>
      <p>Finally, we sum the present values, add net cash (Cash & Short Term Investments minus Total Debt), and divide by shares outstanding.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Free Cash Flows (Y1-5)</td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(sumPvFcf)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(pvTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="subtotal">
              <td>Enterprise Value</td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(enterpriseValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Plus: Net Cash (Debt)</td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(netCash)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td>Total Equity Value</td>
              <td class="num">${formatMillions(equityValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Shares Outstanding</td>
              <td class="num">{formatMillions(sharesOut)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="final-row">
              <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
              <td class="num">{formatCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis Matrix</h2>
      <p>A valuation is only as good as its assumptions. The matrix below shows how Microsoft's intrinsic value per share changes depending on the discount rate (WACC) and terminal growth rate applied.</p>

      <div class="matrix-wrapper">
        <div class="matrix-legend">
          <span>Row = Terminal Growth Rate (2.5% to 4.5%)</span>
          <span>Column = Discount Rate (6.8% to 10.8%)</span>
        </div>
        <table class="matrix-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th></th>
              {drRange.map(dr => <th>{(dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>)}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {tgrRange.map((tgr, rIndex) => (
              <tr>
                <th>{(tgr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
                {drRange.map((dr, cIndex) => {
                  const val = sensitivityMatrix[cIndex][rIndex];
                  const diff = ((val - currentPrice) / currentPrice) * 100;
                  const cellColor = diff > 0 ? '#10b981' : '#ef4444';

                  // Highlight the base case
                  const isBase = dr === discountRate && tgr === terminalGrowthRate;
                  const bgStyle = isBase ? 'background-color: #1a2a40; border: 2px solid #4a8fe7;' : '';

                  return (
                    <td style={bgStyle}>
                      <div class="matrix-cell">
                        <span class="num">{formatCurrency(val)}</span>
                        <span class="matrix-diff" style={`color: ${cellColor}`}>
                          {diff > 0 ? '+' : ''}{diff.toFixed(0)}%
                        </span>
                      </div>
                    </td>
                  )
                })}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Key Risks to This Valuation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>AI Capital Expenditure Drag:</strong> Microsoft is spending tens of billions on AI GPUs and data centers. If the ROI on these investments takes longer than anticipated, Free Cash Flow margins will compress severely over the next 3-5 years.</li>
        <li><strong>Regulatory Scrutiny:</strong> As an undisputed tech monopoly, ongoing antitrust pressures in the EU and US could force structural changes or massive fines, hampering growth.</li>
        <li><strong>Macroeconomic Sensitivity:</strong> While enterprise software is sticky, a severe global recession would still impact Azure consumption growth and seat-license expansions.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Why use a 12% FCF growth rate for Microsoft?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>While Microsoft's revenue may grow faster than 12%, Free Cash Flow is constrained by record-breaking capital expenditures required to build AI infrastructure (data centers, Nvidia GPUs). 12% represents a balanced view where revenue scales aggressively but margins face near-term pressure.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Does Microsoft's debt hurt its intrinsic value?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>No. Microsoft operates with a net cash position. They hold significantly more cash and short-term investments than total debt. In our model, this net cash surplus (approx. ${formatMillions(netCash)} million) is added directly to the enterprise value.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What makes Microsoft's terminal rate higher than GDP?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>A standard company's terminal rate shouldn't exceed inflation/GDP (usually 2-2.5%). However, Microsoft's deep integration into the global economy via Windows, Active Directory, and Azure gives them quasi-sovereign pricing power, allowing them to perpetually raise prices faster than inflation.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <div class="disclaimer-box">
        <p><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This discounted cash flow (DCF) intrinsic value analysis was generated entirely by the Gemini 2.5 Pro large language model for educational and informational purposes. It is not financial advice. Valuation models are highly sensitive to their underlying assumptions. Always conduct your own due diligence or consult a licensed financial advisor before making investment decisions.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</SiteLayout>

